The paper proposes a framework for matching incentives to users with unknown and evolving preferences, which involves designing an algorithm that combines ideas from multiple domains. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), game theory (cs.GT), multi-agent systems (cs.MA), and social and information networks (cs.SI). Among these, machine learning and artificial intelligence seem to be the most likely categories, given the focus on designing an algorithm for personalized recommendations and the use of the upper confidence bound algorithm. Game theory and multi-agent systems are also relevant, as the paper deals with incentivizing agents with dynamic preferences. Social and information networks could be a less likely category, as the paper does not explicitly focus on network analysis or modeling.
